(145, 1, '2018-10-15 18:56:11', '2018-10-15 15:56:11', 'element in a document.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/body.html\" style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: rgb(56, 120, 148); text-decoration: none;\"&gt;<code>&lt;body&gt;</code> ancestor; in the latter case, it applies to the whole document.<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;article&gt; element represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable (e.g., in syndication). Examples include: a forum post, a magazine or newspaper article, or a blog entry.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/article.html\"><code>&lt;article&gt;</code></a>The <strong>HTML <code>&lt;article&gt;</code> element</strong> represents a self-contained composition in a document, page, application, or site, which is intended to be independently distributable or reusable (e.g., in syndication). Examples include: a forum post, a magazine or newspaper article, or a blog entry.<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;aside&gt; element represents a section of a document with content connected tangentially to the main content of the document (often presented as a sidebar).\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/aside.html\"><code>&lt;aside&gt;</code></a>The <strong>HTML <code>&lt;aside&gt;</code> element</strong> represents a section of a document with content connected tangentially to the main content of the document (often presented as a sidebar).<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;footer&gt; element represents a footer for its nearest sectioning content or sectioning root element. A footer typically contains information about the author of the section, copyright data or links to related documents.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/footer.html\"><code>&lt;footer&gt;</code></a>The<strong> HTML <code>&lt;footer&gt;</code> element</strong> represents a footer for its nearest <a href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/HTML/Using_HTML_sections_and_outlines.html#Defining_Sections_in_HTML5\">sectioning content</a> or <a title=\"Sections and Outlines of an HTML5 document#Sectioning root\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/Guide/HTML/Using_HTML_sections_and_outlines.html#Sectioning_root\">sectioning root</a> element. A footer typically contains information about the author of the section, copyright data or links to related documents.<a title=\"The documentation about this has not yet been written; please consider contributing!\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/Heading_Elements.html\"><code>&lt;h1–h6&gt;</code></a><a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;header&gt; element represents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids. It may contain some heading elements but also other elements like a logo, a search form, an author name, and so on.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/header.html\"><code>&lt;header&gt;</code></a>The <strong>HTML <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> element</strong> represents introductory content, typically a group of introductory or navigational aids. It may contain some heading elements but also other elements like a logo, a search form, an author name, and so on.<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;hgroup&gt; element represents a multi-level heading for a section of a document. It groups a set of &lt;h1&gt;–&lt;h6&gt; elements.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/hgroup.html\"><code>&lt;hgroup&gt;</code></a>The <strong>HTML <code>&lt;hgroup&gt;</code> element</strong> represents a multi-level heading for a section of a document. It groups a set of <code><a href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/Heading_Elements.html\">&lt;h1&gt;–&lt;h6&gt;</a></code> elements.<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;nav&gt; element represents a section of a page whose purpose is to provide navigation links, either within the current document or to other documents. Common examples of navigation sections are menus, tables of contents, and indexes.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/nav.html\"><code>&lt;nav&gt;</code></a>The <strong>HTML <code>&lt;nav&gt;</code> element</strong> represents a section of a page whose purpose is to provide navigation links, either within the current document or to other documents. Common examples of navigation sections are menus, tables of contents, and indexes.<a style=\"margin: 0px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; color: #387894; text-decoration: none;\" title=\"The HTML &lt;section&gt; element represents a standalone section of functionality contained within an HTML document, typically with a heading, which doesn\'t have a more specific semantic element to represent it.\" href=\"http://docset.velocity/HTML.docset/developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/section.html\"><code>&lt;section&gt;</code></a>The <strong>HTML <code>&lt;section&gt;</code> element</strong> represents a standalone section of functionality contained within an HTML document, typically with a 